<DocsLayout title="Flow Pipeline Editor">
  <h1>Flow Pipeline Editor</h1>
  <p>
    The Flow Pipeline Editor is a visual, drag-and-drop interface for building encoding workflows. Inspired by tools like FileFlows and Node-RED, it lets you construct complex multi-step pipelines by connecting nodes on a canvas — no scripting required.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each flow defines a complete encoding pipeline: from input selection through analysis, conditional branching, encoding, audio processing, output delivery, and notifications. Flows are reusable and versioned; any flow can be attached to a job at creation time or referenced from a template.
  </p>

  <h2>Accessing the Editor</h2>
  <p>The Flow Pipeline Editor is available from the main navigation under <strong>Flows</strong>.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Flow List</strong> — Navigate to <code>/flows</code> to see all saved flows. Each row shows the flow name, node count, last modified date, and a status badge (active / draft).</li>
    <li><strong>New Flow</strong> — Click <strong>+ New Flow</strong> to open a blank canvas. You will be prompted to name the flow before the editor opens.</li>
    <li><strong>Edit Flow</strong> — Click any flow name or its pencil icon to open the canvas with that flow loaded. Changes are auto-saved as drafts; click <strong>Publish</strong> to make the flow available for job creation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Editor Layout</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Panel</th><th>Location</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Node Sidebar</strong></td>
        <td>Left</td>
        <td>Browse all available node types organised by category. Drag a node onto the canvas to add it to the flow. Use the search box at the top to filter by name.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Canvas</strong></td>
        <td>Centre</td>
        <td>The main editing surface. Nodes appear as cards; draw connections by dragging from an output port to an input port. Scroll to zoom; click-drag on empty space to pan.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Config Panel</strong></td>
        <td>Right</td>
        <td>Displays the configuration form for the currently selected node. Changes apply immediately in draft mode. The panel collapses when no node is selected.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Node Types</h2>
  <p>
    The editor ships with 38 built-in node types across 9 categories. Third-party nodes can be added via the Plugin System.
  </p>

  <h3>Input (2 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>Input File</code></td><td>Reads a single local file path or UNC share for encoding.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Input Folder</code></td><td>Scans a directory (optionally recursive) and queues each matching file as a separate source.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Encoding (5 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>x265</code></td><td>Encodes video with libx265 (HEVC). Configure CRF, preset, and x265-params directly.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>x264</code></td><td>Encodes video with libx264 (H.264). Configure CRF, preset, profile, and level.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>SVT-AV1</code></td><td>Encodes video with SVT-AV1. Configure CRF and encoder preset (0–13).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Stream Copy</code></td><td>Copies the video stream without re-encoding. Fast; no quality loss. Used for remux-only operations.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>NVENC H.265</code></td><td>GPU-accelerated HEVC encoding via NVIDIA NVENC. Requires an NVENC-capable agent.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Analysis (4 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>HDR Detect</code></td><td>Detects HDR format (HDR10, HDR10+, Dolby Vision, HLG) and extracts mastering display metadata and MaxCLL/MaxFALL values.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Scene Scan</code></td><td>Runs PySceneDetect to find scene boundaries. Outputs a boundary list used by chunked encoding for chunk-aligned splitting.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>VMAF Score</code></td><td>Computes VMAF quality score between the source and a reference encode. Results are stored as flow variables.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Probe Info</code></td><td>Runs ffprobe against the source and exposes stream metadata as flow variables (resolution, codec, bitrate, HDR type, etc.).</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Conditions (5 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>File Size</code></td><td>Compares the source file size against a threshold. Has two output ports: <em>true</em> and <em>false</em>.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Resolution</code></td><td>Checks the video resolution against a target (e.g., 4K, 1080p). Has two output ports: <em>true</em> and <em>false</em>.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Codec</code></td><td>Checks whether the source video stream uses a specified codec. Has two output ports: <em>true</em> and <em>false</em>.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>HDR Type</code></td><td>Checks the detected HDR type against a specified value (HDR10, DV, etc.). Has two output ports: <em>true</em> and <em>false</em>.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>File Extension</code></td><td>Checks the source file extension against a specified value. Has two output ports: <em>true</em> and <em>false</em>.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Audio (4 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>FLAC</code></td><td>Encodes audio to FLAC lossless format.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Opus</code></td><td>Encodes audio to Opus format. Configure bitrate and channel layout.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>AAC-LC</code></td><td>Encodes audio to AAC-LC. Configure bitrate and channel layout for broad device compatibility.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Extract Audio</code></td><td>Extracts one or more audio streams to separate files for independent processing.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Output (4 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>Move File</code></td><td>Moves the output file to a specified destination path after encoding.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Copy File</code></td><td>Copies the output file to a specified destination path, leaving the original in place.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Rename</code></td><td>Renames the output file in place. Supports token substitution (e.g., <code>&#123;source_name&#125;</code>).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Set Output Path</code></td><td>Sets the output path variable used by downstream file operation nodes. Supports path templates.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Notifications (4 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>Webhook</code></td><td>Posts a JSON payload to a configured webhook URL. Payload template supports all flow variables.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Discord</code></td><td>Posts a message to a Discord channel via a Discord webhook URL.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Teams</code></td><td>Posts an adaptive card message to a Microsoft Teams channel via an incoming webhook.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Slack</code></td><td>Posts a message to a Slack channel via an incoming webhook URL.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Templates (2 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>Run Template</code></td><td>Executes another saved flow template as a reusable sub-routine. Input and output variables pass through.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Frameserver Template</code></td><td>Pipes frames through a frameserver (e.g., VapourSynth, AviSynth) script before encoding. The script path is configurable.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Flow Control (4 nodes)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Node</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>Chunk Split</code></td><td>Splits the source into segments for parallel encoding across agents. Supports adaptive or fixed chunking strategies.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Merge/Concat</code></td><td>Concatenates encoded chunks or separate files back into a single output container.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Fail Flow</code></td><td>Explicitly terminates the flow with a failure status and a configurable error message.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Delay</code></td><td>Pauses flow execution for a specified number of seconds before continuing to the next node.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Canvas Features</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Snap to grid</strong> — Nodes align to a 20 px grid for tidy layouts. Hold <kbd>Alt</kbd> while dragging to disable snapping.</li>
    <li><strong>MiniMap</strong> — A thumbnail overview of the entire canvas appears in the bottom-right corner. Click anywhere in the minimap to pan to that region.</li>
    <li><strong>Keyboard shortcuts</strong> — <kbd>Ctrl+Z</kbd> / <kbd>Cmd+Z</kbd> to undo, <kbd>Ctrl+Y</kbd> / <kbd>Cmd+Y</kbd> to redo, <kbd>Delete</kbd> or <kbd>Backspace</kbd> to remove selected nodes or edges, <kbd>Ctrl+A</kbd> to select all, <kbd>Space</kbd>+drag to pan.</li>
    <li><strong>Connection validation</strong> — The editor enforces port compatibility. Dragging an incompatible connection highlights the target port in red and shows a tooltip explaining the type mismatch.</li>
    <li><strong>Colored nodes</strong> — Each category has a distinct accent colour for at-a-glance identification: Input (blue), Encoding (violet), Analysis (amber), Conditions (teal), Audio (green), Output (indigo), Notifications (rose), Templates (slate), Flow Control (orange).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Using Flows in Job Creation</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Jobs &gt; New Job</strong>.</li>
    <li>In the <strong>Pipeline</strong> field, select <strong>Flow</strong> from the type dropdown, then choose the desired flow from the list. Published flows appear immediately; draft flows can be selected by enabling the <em>Include drafts</em> toggle.</li>
    <li>Complete the remaining job fields (source, agent tags, priority) and click <strong>Submit</strong>. The flow will execute node-by-node as the job runs, and per-node logs are visible in the job detail view.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>API Reference</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Method</th><th>Path</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>GET</code></td><td><code>/api/v1/flows</code></td><td>List all flows (paginated). Accepts <code>?status=published|draft</code> filter.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>POST</code></td><td><code>/api/v1/flows</code></td><td>Create a new flow. Body: <code>&#123;"name":"string","nodes":[...],"edges":[...]&#125;</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>GET</code></td><td><code>/api/v1/flows/&#123;id&#125;</code></td><td>Get a single flow definition including all nodes and edges.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>PUT</code></td><td><code>/api/v1/flows/&#123;id&#125;</code></td><td>Replace an existing flow definition. Increments the internal version counter.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>DELETE</code></td><td><code>/api/v1/flows/&#123;id&#125;</code></td><td>Delete a flow. Returns <code>409 Conflict</code> if the flow is referenced by any active job or template.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</DocsLayout>
